For further routine use, we propose a 3-gene-combination to be most appropriate including a reasonable low number of genes still preserving very high prediction ability. The best predicting 3-gene-score in our training set included the genes, C-X-C chemokine receptor type 6 (CXCR6), family with sequence similarity 124B (FAM124B), and adenylyl cyclase-associated protein 1 (CAP1) (Fig. 1). While a higher gene expression of CAP1 and FAM124B was associated with adverse survival, a higher expression of CXCR6 led to a better survival. Taking the hazard ratios of the individual genes in multivariate analysis into account and to end up with positive values only, a score ranging from 1 to 4 points (pts) can be calculated as:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
